details: 1913 British suffragette Emmeline Pankhurst sentenced to 3 years in jail
1922 Joseph Stalin is appointed General Secretary of the Russian Communist Party by an ailing Vladimir Lenin
1958 Fidel Castro's rebels attacked Havana
2012 US President Barack Obama officially secures Democratic presidential nomination
2020 London's Nightingale hospital opened by Prince Charles (remotely) after nine days with 4,000 beds to treat COVID-19 patients at the ExCeL Centre
1367 Henry IV of England, King of England and Lord of Ireland (1399-1413), born in Bolingbroke Castle, Lincolnshire, England (d. 1413)
1783 Washington Irving, American writer (Legend of Sleepy Hollow), born in NYC, New York (d. 1859)
1866 J. B. M. Hertzog [Barry Hertzog], South African General and Prime Minister (1924-39), born in Wellington, South Africa (d. 1942)
1934 Jane Goodall, British ethologist (studied African chimps), born in London, England
1964 Ajay Sharma, Indian cricketer (Indian spin all-rounder played one Test 1988), born in Delhi, India
33 Christ, crucified (according to astronomer Humphreys & Waddington)
1680 Shivaji Bhonsle [Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj], Indian warrior and founder of the Maratha Empire, dies of fever and dysentery around the age of 52
1996 Carl Stokes, 1st African American mayor of a major US city (Cleve), dies
2014 Tommy Lynn Sells, American serial killer, executed for murder at 49
2018 David Edgerton, American entrepreneur and founder of Burger King, dies of complications of surgery at 90
1930 2nd Academy Awards: "The Broadway Melody", Warner Baxter & Mary Pickford win. First time Academy Awards are broadcast on the radio.
1978 50th Academy Awards: "Annie Hall", Richard Dreyfuss & Diane Keaton win
1978 Larry King moves his radio show from Miami to Washington, D.C.
2005 WrestleMania XXI, Staples Center, Los Angeles, CA: Batista defeats Triple H
2016 WrestleMania XXXII, AT&T Stadium, Arlington, TX (101,763): Roman Reigns defeats Triple H
1924 Marlon Brando, American actor (The Godfather, A Streetcar Named Desire and On the Waterfront), born in Omaha, Nebraska (d. 2004)
1937 Petunia Pig, Warner Bros. cartoon character created by Frank Tashlin (Looney Tunes and Merrie Melodies series), first debuts in "Porky's Romance"
1961 Eddie Murphy, American actor (SNL, 48 Hours, Beverly Hills Cop, Raw), born in Brooklyn, New York
1974 Wu Jing, Chinese actor and martial artist (Wolf Warrior), born in Beijing, China
1998 Paris Jackson, American actress and daughter of Michael Jackson, born in Los Angeles, California
1993 Dieter Plage, German wildlife filmmaker, dies at 57
1994 Frank G Wells, US company director (Walt Disney Co.), dies in a helicopter crash at 62
1995 Gracita Morales, Spanish actress (Operation Mata Hari), dies at 66
2013 Ruth Prawer Jhabvala, German-American novelist and screenwriter, dies from pulmonary failure at 85
2016 Erik Bauersfeld, American voice actor (Star Wars' Admiral Ackbar "Its a trap"), dies at 93
1960 Elvis Presley records ‘It's Now Or Never’, ‘Fever’ and ‘Are You Lonesome Tonight’ at RCA studios in Nashville, Tennessee
1964 Beatles hold top 6 spots on Sydney Australia record charts
1971 16th Eurovision Song Contest: Severine for Monaco wins singing "Un banc, un arbre, une rue" in Dublin
2007 Rolling Stones guitarist Keith Richards denies saying he smoked his father's ashes in an interview with NME
2008 Mariah Carey overtakes Elvis Presley's record of 17 No. 1 US hits with her 18th ‘Touch My Body’, only The Beatles have more with 20
1922 Doris Day, American singer, animal welfare activist and actress known as the "girl next door" actress, was born in Cincinnati, Ohio (d. 2019)
1941 Philippé Wynne, American soul singer (I'll Be Around), born in Detroit, Michigan (d. 1984)
1963 Tsuyoshi Sekito, Japanese video game composer, born in Osaka, Japan
1965 Nazia Hassan, Pakistani pop singer-songwriter, lawyer and social activist known as "Queen of Pop" in South Asia, born in Karachi, Sindh, Pakistan (d. 2000)
1985 Leona Lewis, English singer (Bleeding Love), born in Islington, London
1930 Emma Albani, Canadian operatic soprano, dies at 82
1996 Booba [Roosevelt Melvin] Barnes, American blues guitarist, dies at 59
2001 Lester "Big Daddy" Kinsey, American Chicago blues singer, guitarist and harmonica player, dies at 74
2003 Homer Banks, American singer and songwriter (Be What You Are), dies at 61
2017 Kishori Amonkar, Indian classical Hindustani singer, dies at 84
1962 American jockey Eddie Arcaro retires after 31 years (24,092 races)
1966 Tom Seaver signs with the Mets for a reported $50,000 bonus
1975 Bobby Fischer stripped of world chess title for refusing to defend it
1993 147th Grand National: race declared void, after 30 of 39 runners carried on racing despite a false start; bookmakers forced to refund estimated £75 million in bets staked
2016 ANA Inspiration Women's Golf, Mission Hills CC: Lydia Ko of New Zealand wins by 1 from Charley Hull & Chun In-gee for her second major title
1928 Earl Lloyd, 1st African American basketball player in the NBA, born in Alexandria, Virginia (d. 2015)
1948 Mary Gordon-Watson, British equestrian 3 day event (Olympic gold 1972), born in Blandford, Dorset
1962 Nancy Filteau, Canadian athlete, 72k judoka (Olympics 1996), born in Swift Current, Saskatchewan
1963 Zakir Khan, Pakistani cricketer (two Tests for Pakistan 1986-89), born in Bannu, Pakistan
1969 Rodney Hampton, American football player, NFL running back (NY Giants), born in Houston, Texas
1915 Andrew Stoddart, English cricketer (England captain) and ruby union player, commits suicide by firearm at 52
1962 Benny "Kid" Paret, American welterweight boxer, dies after a fight at 24
1997 Judy Flannery, American triathlete, killed by a car while training at 56
2007 Eddie Robinson, American College Football Hall of Fame coach (Grambling 408 wins), dies of Alzheimer's disease at 88
2020 Tom Dempsey, American NFL kicker (Pro Bowl, First-team All-Pro 1969; New Orleans Saints; longest winning field goal, 63 yards), dies of COVID-19 complications at 73
